  "prompt": "When the hydronium-ion concentration of a solution is 1\u00d710\u221212 M , what is the pH of the solution?",
  "response": "To determine the pH of a solution when the hydronium ion concentration, \\([H_3O^+]\\), is \\(1 \\times 10^{-12}\\) M, you can use the formula for pH:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log[H_3O^+]\n\\]\n\nGiven that \\([H_3O^+]\\) is \\(1 \\times 10^{-12}\\) M, we can substitute this value into the equation:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log(1 \\times 10^{-12})\n\\]\n\nUsing the properties of logarithms, this simplifies to:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = 12\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the pH of the solution is 12.",
